Ibid., pp. 3, 15. Similarly, Jeroen Gunning and Richard Jackson question the assumption that ‘religious terrorism’ is the product of religious ideology and unpack the distinction between ‘secular’ and ‘religious’ forms of terrorism. Also, Mark Sedgwick argues that al-Qaida’s violence is best understood in terms of classic theories of the political strategy of ‘propaganda of the deed’, as developed by nineteenth-century anarchists; 
